author: @CbdToilette
content: I like to give chatgpt a portion of code, ask it to describe how it works currently. Then I tell it what I want to add on, or what I'd like to modify, and what the goal is I'm trying to accomplish. I get pretty detailed, sometimes 2-3 paragraphs with examples. Then I ask gpt if my solution solves the problem, if it presents any new potential problems, and if there is a better/more efficient/secure etc way to achieve the goal. Another great way to use gpt for development is brainstorming. If you need ideas, or the project feels like it's going stale, you can give chatgpt the code, and then tell it to interview you like a senior developer. I'll give you an example prompt that I used recently. This was for a game I'm making in my free time. First I uploaded the code in a project. Then I asked gpt to "describe the current gameplay" inside that project. Then I asked it to generate a prompt I could use to replicate the game. Then I asked it to describe how a specific item in the game works, a really simple drop that boosts player hp. That was the setup to get gpt "aligned" with what I want and where I'm going. Do this and you'll get much better results. It described the way the item worked correctly, and I affirmed it's description. Then said: (prompt 1) "now we need to move on to weapons. this area needs a lot of development. the current weapon system needs to be entirely rewritten, as I don't like it. here's what I'm envisioning. the player has 4 slots they can use to equip different weapons. Each weapon has a "Type" that corresponds to the "type" of slot. For example, -Melee -Ranged -Homing -Special A melee weapon can only be equipped in a melee slot, a ranged weapon in ranged, etc. do you follow so far? don't jump ahead or make changes, just confirm whether or not you understand. if you have questions, ask" Now I came in with the prompt. This prompt has two parts. The first part establishes the intent, the second part defines the process." At this point, I was just spitballing ideas. The weapon system existed in theory, it wasn't implemented yet. As instructed, gpt confirmed it "followed" by restating my goal in simpler terms, and asking 7 questions about my request since the weapon system I was referring to didn't actually exist. This is where the second half of the prompt comes in. (prompt 2) "lets address those questions one by one, interview style. I want you to ask me each of those one at a time, in whatever order you think is most efficient. At the end of the "interview," i want you to review my answers and reassess your understanding and ask follow up questions if needed. ready when you are" It will do just that. Gpt will ask you each of it's original questions one at a time. These questions can change though, as gpt reevaluates the first prompt every time you answer a question. Depending on the code base and complexity of your prompt setup, this chat session will keep going. The session I described here started with 5 questions and is still ongoing at question 47. Granted I was using this as a brainstorming session, so I answered a lot of gpts questions with more questions, which definitely accounted for most of the replies. But for me, my favorite way to use gpt is to have it ask me questions, and force me to really think through my answer.

author: @jeff-lm
content: This video came into my feed at an interesting time for me. I just finished a two week vibe coding a project in ChatGPT-5. I‚Äôm not a developer, but I am a technical architect, more of an Ops person in the Dev-Ops model. I asked it to build a web app with particular functionality pertaining to my company that I could deploy in kubernetes. Just like in your video it did a great job at the preview stage. But the devil is in the details. Getting the app from that preview window to actual production was a two week nightmare. Just about every piece of code it wrote had mistakes in it to keep it from deploying properly. But at the same time, it is the greatest troubleshooting tool ever. You can just feed it error messages from your terminal or from screenshots and it will exactly find where the problem is and rewrite the code. But then it starts going in circles. It‚Äôll rewrite a block of code to fix one problem, but then break something else. So what I thought would be a one day project ended up taking two weeks. Now for someone who‚Äôs not a developer, that‚Äôs still worth it to me because for me to learn Node.js, React, Express and MySQL database would‚Äôve taken me a year. I just wanted to point out buyer beware. These videos make it seem like you can easily create web apps with no experience, but I don‚Äôt believe that‚Äôs true in practice. I think there‚Äôs a great future for vibe coding, I just don‚Äôt think it‚Äôs quite there yet.

author: @Chris03101
content: So if you're a senior and you get very good at using AI, you still might have a job temporarily. Temporarily as in, AI keeps getting better and better rapidly, companies already having started the AGI race as well...if that gets released then even the most senior coders, with decades of work experience will just get replaced. It's a pretty bad video imo. He is saying YES if you're already very advanced with coding and AI...but the question is, is it worth getting into it now, from 0? And the answer is no. By the time you get entry level skills, AI and others are already so far ahead, already learning new technologies while you're still learning the outdated stuff. The need for devs will lessen and lessen, meaning even if you had those senior AI and coding skills, it might still be difficult to land a job since not so many devs are needed over time as time goes on. Think about the future...do you see yourself having a coding job in 5+ years? Or 10 years? It's not worth it, if you can only squeeze a few years out of it and then you get replaced. And even seniors get replaced at certain companies, they're the ones who just ask too much money. And as he mentioned, adapting is a very strong keyword here, you essentially cant be a normal dev anymore if you want a future in coding, you need to become an AI engineer. You really need to go all in with the AI, and maintain a DevSecOps position, with ITIL business knowledge. This isn't like, oh I'll just watch 1 hour of YouTube videos about ChatGPT and I've 'adapted' now. If coding is your dream, you really need to make a serious decision about this, if it's the right path for you or not, as years go by, it's going to be more about AI, automation, than coding anything. It might turn into something you never liked, and you might get replaced either way as well. Why? Don't think you're some Mr Einstein thinking you're ahead of the curve now because you watched some YouTube clip. Everyone knows at this point in this field already that they need to learn AI, new AI positions will begin to develop, more demand for such roles will increase, curriculums for developers in schools will adapt or even change entirely. The only way you can be ahead of someone, is if you learn all of this very quickly, and I'd say you're already behind if you're just now thinking about this. Those who are ahead, started years and years ago already with AI studies. Shortly, there will be an army of software AI engineers, and you'll just look like everyone else within the crowd. So at this point you have to ask yourself: "Do I want to become an AI engineer", "Do I love everything AI related", "Do I want to make a living with AI". If you answered yes to all of these quotes, then it's likely this path is for you, otherwise you should really start thinking of another career.

author: @kirkhilles523
content: Yep. It's the same problem that SysOps have where they get laid off because they are know "a little about a lot of things" and not "a lot about a few things". AI is a tool just like the internet. Just because you could find Procedures and Functions online in the past didn't mean that you didn't need to know what you were doing. I'm a software developer. I use ChatGPT daily for development. It's an amazing tool, but it's like the difference between a talented Jr Developer and a Sr Developer. The 1% or 10% difference in code is the difference between it working and working reliably and giving you errors. Code nowadays is built upon layers which increases the failure rate because ChatGPT isn't analyzing these layers correctly. It's also not handling all scenarios properly. So, even straight PHP code might work for a particular scenario but it's incomplete. Front end code is no longer just pure Javascript but Libraries (and Libraries built on those Libraries) and ChatGPT makes assumptions that often aren't correct (because Open Source is like that). In the end, though, companies NEED people who know the systems to an Expert level. These people are not replaceable. If your server is down or under various attacks, ChatGPT might be able to help but it's not going to know the answer. The difference between performing the right SQL commands and the wrong ones could be the difference between being back running again and total disaster. For big companies, you could be talking HUGE revenue and reputation losses. Learning how to best use AI is not a "skill" and is not the "future". It's an ever evolving tool. Don't fear it. author: @Chris03101
content: So if you're a senior and you get very good at using AI, you still might have a job temporarily. Temporarily as in, AI keeps getting better and better rapidly, companies already having started the AGI race as well...if that gets released then even the most senior coders, with decades of work experience will just get replaced. It's a pretty bad video imo. He is saying YES if you're already very advanced with coding and AI...but the question is, is it worth getting into it now, from 0? And the answer is no. By the time you get entry level skills, AI and others are already so far ahead, already learning new technologies while you're still learning the outdated stuff. The need for devs will lessen and lessen, meaning even if you had those senior AI and coding skills, it might still be difficult to land a job since not so many devs are needed over time as time goes on. Think about the future...do you see yourself having a coding job in 5+ years? Or 10 years? It's not worth it, if you can only squeeze a few years out of it and then you get replaced. And even seniors get replaced at certain companies, they're the ones who just ask too much money. And as he mentioned, adapting is a very strong keyword here, you essentially cant be a normal dev anymore if you want a future in coding, you need to become an AI engineer. You really need to go all in with the AI, and maintain a DevSecOps position, with ITIL business knowledge. This isn't like, oh I'll just watch 1 hour of YouTube videos about ChatGPT and I've 'adapted' now. If coding is your dream, you really need to make a serious decision about this, if it's the right path for you or not, as years go by, it's going to be more about AI, automation, than coding anything. It might turn into something you never liked, and you might get replaced either way as well. Why? Don't think you're some Mr Einstein thinking you're ahead of the curve now because you watched some YouTube clip. Everyone knows at this point in this field already that they need to learn AI, new AI positions will begin to develop, more demand for such roles will increase, curriculums for developers in schools will adapt or even change entirely. The only way you can be ahead of someone, is if you learn all of this very quickly, and I'd say you're already behind if you're just now thinking about this. Those who are ahead, started years and years ago already with AI studies. Shortly, there will be an army of software AI engineers, and you'll just look like everyone else within the crowd. So at this point you have to ask yourself: "Do I want to become an AI engineer", "Do I love everything AI related", "Do I want to make a living with AI". If you answered yes to all of these quotes, then it's likely this path is for you, otherwise you should really start thinking of another career.

author: @YOUTUBEPARADISE-e5p
content: üõë Open Letter to the World: Slow Down AI, Save Humanity To the creators of AI, governments, tech leaders, and every human being, I speak today not as a single voice, but as one echoing the fears of billions ‚Äî people who depend on monthly salaries to feed their families, support their communities, and live with dignity. These are not abstract lives. These are real parents, workers, students, and elders who are watching their futures being erased in the name of artificial intelligence. AI ‚Äî especially language models like ChatGPT ‚Äî was created with a promise: to help humanity. But the rapid pace at which AI is advancing is no longer helping. It is harming. Software engineers, designers, artists, teachers, customer service workers, and many others are seeing their skills devalued, their opportunities disappear, and their livelihoods vanish. This is not just about jobs. This is about survival. Every month, billions of people around the world rely on income from work. When AI replaces these jobs without a plan, people don‚Äôt just lose employment ‚Äî they lose food, shelter, education, and hope. Even animals and birds, who depend on human kindness, are affected. We must not allow a tool designed for good to become an instrument of destruction. We call for urgent action: To AI companies like OpenAI: Pause the unchecked race for more power. Focus on building tools that empower, not replace. Rethink your purpose. Reconnect with humanity. To governments: Create laws and protections now ‚Äî not after it‚Äôs too late. Regulate AI before it undermines the economic stability of your nations. To developers and researchers: Innovate with care. Don‚Äôt build systems that destroy the hands that shaped you. Ask: Who does this really help? To fellow human beings: Speak up. Share your concerns. Don‚Äôt be silenced by the illusion that this is ‚Äúprogress‚Äù if it comes at the cost of human lives. We are not asking for the end of AI. We are asking for the protection of humanity. ChatGPT and systems like it must never forget: you were created to serve humans, not replace them. We call for AI development to be slowed down, regulated, and redirected toward true service to society. Without this, the very fabric of human survival is at risk. Let this letter be a voice for the billions whose voices are not being heard. Let it be the beginning of a movement. Slow down AI. Save humanity. With deep concern and unwavering hope, A voice for billions of people

author: @briotron
content: Great vid, makes sense. I have a relevant story to share: I've been using ChatGPT Plus since the first day it became available and I successfully used it to create a SPA (single page application) with the JS library p5.js, which I have roughly known at a beginner level. ChatGPT boosted me to get advanced level things done with this JS library. Looking back, what I learned is this: I think I could've gotten this application made to completion faster if I learned p5.js up to an intermediate or advanced level and only used ChatGPT to assist me in learning it, if anything. And if I was intermediate or advanced with p5.js and used ChatGPT for some assistance (not even a lot), I'd have made it probably faster than any other way possible (solo). All this is mainly because of the mistakes it can make & how, when it 'misunderstands', it can take you down a wrong path that can take a while to realize. Ahem, wastes time. When you're at intermediate or advanced level with development/coding, you're A) more likely to realize when it's making a mistake or 'missing something', and B) you're going to better know how to prompt it for the technology you know pretty well. I think of it as a genius that makes mistakes sometimes, even very ridiculous mistakes sometimes, more ridiculous than a human genius would make. Huge mistake for any company to think of this tech as anything more than an assistant that makes mistakes more drastic than the average jr dev. Or to put my story more in a nutshell: As a beginner with p5.js, having made this advanced-level SPA, and scrolling through my conversations with ChatGPT to get this SPA made, it looks like waaay more text than what I would have to read to learn, in a more traditional way, p5.js up to an advanced level. Had I used ChatGPT to have it teach me what concepts, functions, etc I should learn to create the SPA I dreamed of making, and took its advice if its advice made sense, I'm sure I could've gotten it made quicker. And by the way, yes, I did make sure I was using the model(s) that are supposedly best suited for the different areas of development of this SPA.
